    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-VI-5-sols">
        <title><m>\S VI.5</m>: L'Hospital's Rule</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Motivation: L'Hospital's Rule </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Derivatives are defined by a limit. They can also help us evaluate certain limits, which is 
                            the application explored in this section.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Limit Notation (Review)</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Recall that we can use limit notation to describe the end behavior of functions, as well as when 
                            functions grow arbitrarily large or small. For example,
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{x^2+2}{2x^2+x} = \frac{1}{2}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to - \infty} \frac{x^2+2}{2x^2+x} = \frac{1}{2}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \infty} x^3 = \infty</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to - \infty} x^3 = - \infty</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>L'Hospital's Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> be differentiable functions. If 
                            <me>
                                \lim_{x\to a} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \sim \frac{0}{0}  \hspace{2cm} \text{      OR       } \,\,\, \lim_{x\to a} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \sim \pm \frac{\infty}{\infty}
                            </me>
                            then
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                           <m>  \lim_{x\to a} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} =  \lim_{x\to a} \frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)} </m>, provided this limit 
                           exists or is <m>\pm \infty</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Example: L'Hospital's Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{x}{e^x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{\sin(x)}{x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{x}{e^x} = \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{1}{e^x} = 0</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{\sin(x)}{x} = \lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{\cos(x)}{1} = 1</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: L'Hospital's Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 1 } \frac{x-1}{\ln(x)}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \frac{\pi}{2} } \frac{\sin(x)}{x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{x^2}{e^x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{\ln(x)}{x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{5\cos(x)-5}{x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{2e^x-2}{x^2-3x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 1 } \frac{x-1}{\ln(x)} = \lim_{x \to 1 } \frac{1}{1/x} =1</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \frac{\pi}{2} } \frac{\sin(x)}{x}= \frac{2}{\pi}</m> (Note: LH rule does not apply)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{x^2}{e^x}=\lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{2x}{e^x} =\lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{2}{e^x} = 0</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{\ln(x)}{x} = \lim_{x \to \infty } \frac{1/x}{1} = 0</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{5\cos(x)-5}{x} = \lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{-5\sin(x)}{1} = 0</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{2e^x-2}{x^2-3x} = \lim_{x \to 0 } \frac{2e^x}{2x-3} = -\frac{2}{3} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>
            </page>

